{
  day: 28,
  title: "Money, Banks, and Payments",
  titleNative: "Geld, banken en betalingen",
  focus: "The Netherlands is very card-friendly, and some places do not accept cash. These words help you handle payments, ATMs, and card issues.",
  vocab: [{ nl: "geld", en: "money", ipa: "khelt" }, { nl: "bank", en: "bank", ipa: "bahnk" }, { nl: "pinautomaat", en: "ATM", ipa: "PIN-ow-toh-maat" }, { nl: "kaart", en: "card", ipa: "kaart" }, { nl: "contant", en: "cash", ipa: "kon-TAHNT" }, { nl: "wisselgeld", en: "change", ipa: "VIS-ul-khelt" }, { nl: "betaling", en: "payment", ipa: "buh-TAH-ling" }, { nl: "bon", en: "receipt", ipa: "bon" }, { nl: "rekening", en: "bill/account", ipa: "RAY-kuh-ning" }, { nl: "fooi", en: "tip", ipa: "foy" }],
  phrases: [{ nl: "Kan ik met kaart betalen?", en: "Can I pay by card?", ipa: "kan ik met kaart buh-TAH-lun" }, { nl: "Neemt u contant geld aan?", en: "Do you accept cash?", ipa: "naymt ew kon-TAHNT khelt aan" }, { nl: "Waar is een pinautomaat?", en: "Where is an ATM?", ipa: "vaar is un PIN-ow-toh-maat" }, { nl: "Mijn kaart werkt niet.", en: "My card does not work.", ipa: "mayn kaart werkt neet" }, { nl: "Mag ik de bon?", en: "May I have the receipt?", ipa: "makh ik duh bon" }, { nl: "Is de fooi inbegrepen?", en: "Is the tip included?", ipa: "is duh foy IN-buh-khray-pun" }],
  grammar: "Betalen means “to pay,” and the phrase met kaart betalen is very common. A Dutch bill can be de rekening, while bon usually means the receipt. Fooi means tip, but tipping in the Netherlands is usually modest and optional for good service.",
  practice: ["Ask whether you can pay by card.", "Ask if cash is accepted.", "Say your card does not work.", "Ask where the nearest ATM is.", "Practice asking whether the tip is included."]
},
{
  day: 29,
  title: "Local Culture and Etiquette",
  titleNative: "Lokale cultuur en etiquette",
  focus: "Understanding Dutch habits helps you avoid awkward moments. Direct communication, punctuality, cycling rules, and simple politeness are part of everyday life.",
  vocab: [{ nl: "op tijd", en: "on time", ipa: "op tayt" }, { nl: "direct", en: "direct", ipa: "dee-REKT" }, { nl: "beleefd", en: "polite", ipa: "buh-LAYFT" }, { nl: "regel", en: "rule", ipa: "RAY-khul" }, { nl: "fietsbel", en: "bike bell", ipa: "FEETS-bel" }, { nl: "rij", en: "line/queue", ipa: "ray" }, { nl: "afspraak", en: "appointment", ipa: "AF-spraak" }, { nl: "rustig", en: "calm/quiet", ipa: "RUS-tukh" }, { nl: "respect", en: "respect", ipa: "res-PEKT" }, { nl: "normaal", en: "normal", ipa: "nor-MAAL" }],
  phrases: [{ nl: "Ik ben op tijd.", en: "I am on time.", ipa: "ik ben op tayt" }, { nl: "Sorry, ik wist het niet.", en: "Sorry, I did not know.", ipa: "SOR-ee, ik vist hut neet" }, { nl: "Is dit normaal hier?", en: "Is this normal here?", ipa: "is dit nor-MAAL heer" }, { nl: "Mag ik hier zitten?", en: "May I sit here?", ipa: "makh ik heer ZIT-tun" }, { nl: "Ik wacht in de rij.", en: "I am waiting in line.", ipa: "ik vakht in duh ray" }, { nl: "Bedankt voor de uitleg.", en: "Thanks for the explanation.", ipa: "buh-DAHNKT voor duh OWT-lekh" }],
  grammar: "Dutch culture values punctuality and directness, but direct does not usually mean rude. Sorry, ik wist het niet is useful when you accidentally break an unfamiliar rule. Mag ik...? remains your polite tool for asking permission.",
  practice: ["Say that you are on time.", "Ask if you may sit somewhere.", "Apologize and say you did not know.", "Practice saying you are waiting in line.", "Write three Dutch etiquette tips in English, then attach one Dutch phrase to each."]
},
{
  day: 30,
  title: "Travel Review and Real-Life Confidence",
  titleNative: "Reisoverzicht en zelfvertrouwen",
  focus: "This final day brings together the language you need for a complete trip through the Netherlands. You should now be able to greet, ask, order, travel, solve problems, and connect politely.",
  vocab: [{ nl: "reis", en: "trip", ipa: "rays" }, { nl: "ervaring", en: "experience", ipa: "er-VAH-ring" }, { nl: "vraag", en: "question", ipa: "vraakh" }, { nl: "antwoord", en: "answer", ipa: "ANT-woord" }, { nl: "gesprek", en: "conversation", ipa: "khuh-SPREK" }, { nl: "stad", en: "city", ipa: "stat" }, { nl: "station", en: "station", ipa: "stah-SYON" }, { nl: "hotel", en: "hotel", ipa: "hoh-TEL" }, { nl: "restaurant", en: "restaurant", ipa: "res-toh-RAHNT" }, { nl: "thuis", en: "home", ipa: "tows" }],
  phrases: [{ nl: "Ik heb een vraag.", en: "I have a question.", ipa: "ik heb un vraakh" }, { nl: "Kunt u mij helpen?", en: "Can you help me?", ipa: "kunt ew may HEL-pun" }, { nl: "Ik wil graag bestellen.", en: "I would like to order.", ipa: "ik vil khraakh buh-STEL-lun" }, { nl: "Ik zoek mijn hotel.", en: "I am looking for my hotel.", ipa: "ik zook mayn hoh-TEL" }, { nl: "Dat was een mooie ervaring.", en: "That was a beautiful experience.", ipa: "dat vas un MOY-uh er-VAH-ring" }, { nl: "Ik kom graag terug.", en: "I would gladly come back.", ipa: "ik kom khraakh trukh" }],
  grammar: "Your most flexible Dutch structures are Ik heb..., Ik wil graag..., Mag ik..., Waar is..., and Kunt u.... With these, you can handle many real travel situations even with limited vocabulary. Focus on being clear, polite, and willing to repeat yourself.",
  practice: ["Create a full travel day in Dutch using hotel, café, train, and restaurant phrases.", "Ask for help, directions, and a price in three separate sentences.", "Order food and ask for the bill.", "Describe one travel experience using mooi or leuk.", "Record yourself speaking a one-minute Dutch travel introduction."]
}
